<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-071  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 071.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 16 1989 v10 n3 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Netronix touts first 'plastic' LAN: distance no problem.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Teri.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Netronix (Petaluma, CA) introduces the 2Mbps Fiberstar PC network,which supports both plastic and glass optical fiber in an opticallocal area network (LAN).andP;  Plastic fibers offer users spans of upto 500 feet between nodes, reduced installation expenses andproblems, easier monitoring and problem isolation because of theuse of visible light, reduced 'looping' problems, and lessmaintenance costs.andP;  Fiberstar uses glass fiber to connect moredistant nodes up to 6,000 feet apart.andP;  The architecture consistsof $2,195 16-port hubs for device connection and signalregeneration, $595 or $895 adapter boards (depending on whetherthey are purchased with TCP-IP) for PCs, cable, and auxiliaryhardware.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Netronix Fiberstar PC (Local area network).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSpecificationsSystem DesignLocal Area NetworksOptical CommunicationsFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Representation of a Netronix Fiberstar network. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>